Alert to pesticides ingested by children
A child of 10 years consumed in a day 81 different chemicals, according to a study published Wednesday by the association Generations Futures (former Movement for Rights and the respect of future generations).
The association, which cautions that its results "were not statistically significant in light of the low number of samples analyzed, but are illustrative of the problem dealt with," has purchased between July and September foods usually consumed four meals and a snack in one day by a child a dozen years in the Oise supermarkets and Paris.
These meals types, including the formal recommendations - five fruits and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 litre of water per day - as well as sweets, were examined by laboratories in search of chemical substances, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The balance sheet of the tax base is damning: 81 chemicals including 42 are probable or possible carcinogens and five substances are carcinogenic some and 37 substances that may act as endocrine disrupters (EP), according to studies of several institutions such as the International Centre for Research on Cancer.
"Even if, in almost all cases, the legal limits for each substance taken individually are not exceeded, you can see in our investigation that the reality of consumer exposure to potentially carcinogenic contaminants and/or MOU is worrying," notes the association.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen potential carcinogenic residues and three found some carcinogens and almost two dozen residues that can disrupt the hormonal system.
Apple, imported from Brazil, planned as a snack in the study, presents traces of six chemicals with a fungicide yet banned in France.
Same thing for green beans from Kenya, included in the luncheon, on which the study has detected traces of a powerful insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, chopped steak, canned tuna, and even the loaves of bread and chewing gum were laden with pesticides and other chemicals.
In tap water analyses have revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
For dinner, steak salmon was the most "rich" with 34 residue chemicals detected and even the examination of the plastic base used to heat the meal in the microwave was not free.
The risk final for the "cocktails of contaminants" consumer "is probably underestimated," according to the study.
Europe Ecology Alliance - The Greens (EE, LV), for its part, has proposed "faced with the urgency of the situation" to establish a moratorium on the use of pesticides, in order to stop "the increase in diseases of civilisation."
In July, a study of the European agency for food safety (EFSA) reported the presence of residues of pesticides 365 different identified in fruits and vegetables consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
